Uncontrollable human pollution and global disasters are major environmental problems that result from the negative impact of human activities on the planet.  Uncontrollable human pollution encompasses various forms of pollution, such as air, water and soil pollution, as well as plastic pollution, greenhouse gas emissions and the destruction of biodiversity  .  These human actions have devastating consequences, including climate change, extreme weather events, rising sea levels, massive deforestation, depletion of natural resources, overfishing, destruction of natural habitats, chemical contamination,  and many others.  These problems are leading to global disasters such as floods, wildfires, droughts, more powerful hurricanes, melting ice caps, and the loss of thousands of animal and plant species. Dear Mr. Leonardo DiCaprio and to all the noble souls, My name is Altay Ainebek, known as The Rainman. I stand here, amidst the remnants of what was once a great sea, to speak for those who suffer daily from this environmental catastrophe. ¬† Imagine living in a world where every breath you take carries the sting of salt. Where your crops fail, your water is tainted, and the land that once sustained you has turned to dust. This is the harsh reality for millions of people across Central Asia. The salt from the dried seabed of the Aral Sea is carried by the wind, spreading far and wide, poisoning the soil, water, and air for thousands of kilometres. ¬† But the devastation doesn‚Äôt stop there. The salt, carried by these relentless winds, is now reaching the mighty Himalayas, once the ‚ÄòWater Towers of Asia.‚Äô The salt is accelerating the melting of the glaciers, those life-giving masses of ice that have sustained billions for centuries. As the glaciers melt, the effects are felt far beyond these mountains ‚Äì affecting humans, vegetation, agriculture, and entire ecosystems. ¬† This salt, a silent and insidious force, is not only eroding the land but also the very essence of life in this region. It‚Äôs making the glaciers melt at an alarming rate, disrupting the delicate balance of nature and threatening the future of generations to come. ¬† But there is hope. At ICCCT, we are committed to reversing these disasters through innovative rain enhancement technologies. We are working to bring back the rains, to cleanse the air, to restore the land, and to protect the glaciers from this creeping menace. ¬† To all the noble souls dedicated to climate change mitigation, I call upon you to join us in this critical mission. #ad POV: humidity can ü§† you? Sweating is a superpower? You probably know that your body sweats to cool off. You probably do NOT know that sweating is not as good at cooling you down when the air is very humid. This can turn into big trouble when high temperatures and high humidity are combined.  "Lethal humidity" can occur around temperatures of 35c (95f) combined with humidity around 90%+. If you don't have access to another way to get cool, those conditions can lead to big health issues within ~6 hours. The kicker is that, as global temperatures rise, global humidity rises, too. (When bodies of water get warmer, more of that water tends to evaporate into the air, increasing the humidity) There are things that we can do to reduce the rate of climate change. We need to reduce our dependence/usage of burning fossil fuels, for example by reducing subsidies for fossil fuel-based industries and by incentivizing greener energies. Although personal choices contribute to the overall picture of climate change, we really need to change the decisions from the largest corporate entities. This can be done through regulatory action, but that will only happen once enough people are DEMANDING action from their elected representatives. Please help spread this information to other people. This is important for the eventual fate of our species. (And having the billionaires escape to another planet does not strike me as a very good solution.) [Note on hunting: There are some peoples today who are thought to still sometimes use "persistence hunting" to hunt prey, taking advantage of humans' ability to sweat and dissipate heat. Some of our ancestors may have occasionally used this method of hunting, along with other more common methods, including the use of tools. It is debated as common of a method of hunting it was for our ancestors, but it appears that it was used at least occasionally by various peoples through history] Embrace your sweatiness - it may be a lifesaver! #pushforpositivepower #science #healthy #medicine #climatechange #environment #environmentalism #lethalhumidity #todayilearned #til

The Liter of Light project, initiated by the My Shelter Foundation in the Philippines, provides an innovative and cost-effective solution to the electricity crisis in low-income communities by using sunlight-powered "bulbs" made from discarded plastic bottles. These bulbs are created by filling plastic bottles with a solution of water and bleach, which are then installed into holes cut in the corrugated iron roofs of shanty town homes. The bleach prevents algae growth, while the water refracts sunlight, producing an illumination equivalent to a 55-watt bulb during daylight hours. This simple yet effective technology, adapted from Alfredo Moser's 2002 design with enhancements from MIT students, not only provides much-needed light but also enhances safety by reducing reliance on candles, thus mitigating fire risks.   üé• Source: [real.mrwhy | TikTok] #fyp #foryou #Sustainability #ecofriendly #climatechange  #architecture #arch #archviz #archlovers #architect  #landscapephotography #landscapelovers #landscapedesign #landscapearchitecture #nuelarchitect  #gardendesign #archilovers #archilovers #architecturephotography  #architecturelovers #architectural #archdigest #architecturedesing #design #Interiordesign #homedesing #graphicdesing #landscape

Happy #indigenouspeoplesday ! When I drew this comic 3 years ago I had NO idea how far it would reach. I got a wild amount of vile colonial tantrums in the comments, but also a lot of love, and asking for more ‚ô•Ô∏è However, the goal of this comic was to inspire people to do your OWN research on indigenous history. To question everything we have been taught, and everything that has been pointedly left out. This erasure, this ‚Äúforgetting‚Äù, of history is not just of the past‚Ä¶ it is happening now: - Across so-called Canada, the US, and US-occupied islands, native women are unalived at 10-12x the rate of non-native people, and are the most likely to go missing without being searched for by the law. #mmiw #searchthelandfills  - Native reservations have the highest rates of poverty in the US, with over HALF of tribal homes with no access to clean water (with more joining this list by the year) - Native people are 6-10x more likely to be unhoused than the rest of the population, and native teens suffer unaliving onesself rates higher than any other demographic. This list of modern day geno c1de goes on (thank you for compiling @theindigenousanarchist ‚Ä¶) and yet take a look at those environmental stats üëÄ !! Native people manage to do SO much for the planet as a whole, thanklessly, and with all this stacked against them. Don‚Äôt even let me start on the fight in south america. Could you imagine if there was help? #landback is resistance to geno c1de, and it is the key to saving our warming earth. So look into it and the other hashtags. Because a cartoon goose isn‚Äôt a subsitute for a real education.  All love to my grandparents, who kept a map of turtle island with its tribal territories on their wall always. Who passed on their Tsalagi & Saponi heritage to me. Love and solidarity always. Weak to moderate explosions continue to occur from the summit vent at approximately regular intervals of 8 to 10 per hour. Saudi Arabia Blocking Climate Change Deal #usa #climatechange  Saudi Arabia is allegedly trying to block a global deal to fight Climate Change at the UN. In the deal, countries are wanting to call for a phasing out of fossil fuels in order to combat climate change. Saudi flat out opposes this, and has allegedly been skillful at blocking discussions and delaying talks. All 198 nations at the UN have to agree to a climate deal in order for it to take effect. Other countries are trying to shape the deal. The U.S. wants caveats in the fossil fuel phaseout language while China and India are opposing language that would single out coal. Iran and Russia are seeking protection for natural gas. While Iraq has said that ending gas and oil could devastate countries that rely on them for income and are asking that the deal include more aid from wealthier countries. But Saudi Arabia stands alone in their opposition. Even their neighbor, the UAE, who is also a major oil producer, has taken the stance that transitioning away from fossil fuels is essential. This split can be explained by the UAE making a great effort to be a global destination and to have an economy that is multifaceted while Saudi has struggled to produce an economy beyond oil.

Why are all the places I love on fire?  I‚Äôve been grappling with this lately. While I am not directly impacted by the fires in Jasper, the North Cascades, or elsewhere, I‚Äôm left with concerns about our future. . When I first hit the road in 2021, I fell in love with the North Cascades. I spent every moment I could exploring out here, even just to hike into a cloud to see nothing; I still loved it.  . The North Cascades was where I saw my first mountain goat, and it was my best encounter with this animal ever. It was also where I first hiked a trail and saw backpackers and thought, ‚ÄúWow, that would be cool to do.‚Äù  . When people ask me what my favorite parks are, it always makes the list. It‚Äôs partly for the memories but also because it‚Äôs such a crazy, beautiful, and wild place I‚Äôve been dreaming of returning soon to explore more. In 2021, the East side of the park was closed due to fires, and as of August 11th, there are four active fires in and around the park, with numerous closures. This leaves me to grapple with the question: Is this our future? . We often forget that there‚Äôs a loss in many ways in the wake of these wildfires. It‚Äôs not just the loss of your vacation plans or being unable to do a hike you wanted to do, but the loss of community and economy. These communities outside of parks support us as adventurers and explorers to be there. I do hate to see the devastation and destruction of natural landscapes, and I wonder where these mountain goats are now. But we also need to think of and acknowledge what these losses are like for the people who helped us be able to be there in the first place: the rangers, the shopkeepers, the tour guides, the campground hosts, gas station attendants, and more. The people who live and work here allow me to enjoy this incredible landscape. Thank you. . While I hate to watch it happen, it‚Äôs not just about me and losing places I love; it‚Äôs about so much more.  . #NorthCascades #WildfireSeason #ProtectOurParks #ConservationMatters #PublicLands #ClimateChange #WildlifeConservation #OutdoorCommunity #EnvironmentalImpact #LoveOurParks #WildfireAwareness #NatureConservation #HikingAdventures #ParkRangers #CommunitySupport #NatureLoss #ExploreResponsibly #MountainGoats #SaveOurWildPlaces #PreserveNature
